close_symbols: Definitions of object table/array(s) and their element structure/field sizes (the global object storage read/written by ObjectIdToArrayIndex/ObjectIndexFromToken)
explanation:
You must inspect any called functions and the data they operate on to determine whether any string.h routine (memcpy/memmove/memset/strcmp/strcpy/strncpy/strcat/strncat/strlen/etc.) is invoked in a way that can access out-of-bounds memory. For that purpose include:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: direct callee of OS_MutSemDelete; its body may call string functions or copy buffers.
- OS_MutSemDelete_Impl: direct callee that performs the actual delete work; may manipulate token or object fields with string/buffer operations.
- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete: finalization routine called unconditionally after the impl; may perform notifications or cleanup that use string ops.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit / OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel / OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish: transaction helpers invoked by ObjectIdGetById/FinalizeDelete; transaction code often copies or restores object state and may use string functions.
- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex / OS_ObjectIdConvertToken: low-level helpers that convert object IDs/tokens to array indices or extract token fields; these are the most likely places to see memcpy/strncpy/strlen or buffer-indexing that could violate bounds.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: used by the Impl; may index into object arrays or copy fields.
- OS_NotifyEvent: notification code can format event payloads or names using string routines.
- OS_object_token_t (type definition) and osal_id_t (typedef): the layout and sizes of fields (char arrays, pointers, lengths) are required to judge whether string/buffer operations are bounded.
- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE, OS_LOCK_MODE_EXCLUSIVE, OS_SUCCESS: constants/macros that affect control flow and which code paths (and therefore which string operations) are executed.
- Definitions of the global object table/array(s) and their element structure/field sizes referenced by ObjectIdToArrayIndex/ObjectIndexFromToken: to determine buffer sizes and valid index ranges for any copies or length computations.

Together these symbols allow the next analyst to locate every call site and data buffer involved in the deletion path and verify whether any string.h function is used with pointer/length arguments that could access beyond object bounds.
